Police union POPCRU has welcomed Fikile Mbalula&#8217;s appointment as the Minister of Police saying they faith he will address the many challenges facing society.&#8221; We are of the view that the minister will indeed prioritise the completion of the established Ministerial Transformation Task team which is looking into reviewing all SAPS policies, national instructions, standing orders, working environment and living conditions of our men and women in blue,&#8221; said Popcru spokesperson Richard Mamabolo.The change in the police ministry is one of a host of changes President Jacob Zuma has made to his cabinet.I&#8217;m reading your messages, Thankyou honorable tweeps. Huge task ahead but nothing can&#8217;t be achieved working with you. SALUTE pic.twitter.com/n3c73abU0N Mbalula Fikile (@MbalulaFikile) March 30, 2017Mbalula will now move from the Sports and Recreation ministry which will now be lead by former Public Works Minister Thulas Nxesi.Now former Police minister Nathi Nhleko will replace Nxesi as the Minister of Public Works.The swearing in ceremony of Zuma s new look cabinet was expected to take place on Friday evening at the Sefako Makgatho Presidential Guest House in Tshwane.However, the DA has turned to the Western Cape High Court to file an urgent court application to halt the swearing in of new ministers.The Organisation Undoing Tax Abuse (OUTA) has also announced that it &#8220;is exploring legal action&#8221; against the cabinet reshuffle.&#8211;TNA Reporter